status_message:
6-year-old Emanuel Diaz-Mairena suffered a traumatic brain injury after he was hit by a car while playing ball with his brother Richard, 8. Last year, Wish Book donors bought iPads for both boys to help with their schooling and donated a bedroom set. 

Help us grant wishes to more South Florida families this holiday season. There are still a few hours left to support Wish Book through #GiveMiamiDay. Donate TODAY and a percentage of your gift will be matched by The Miami Foundation.

Link to donate: http://hrld.us/givemiamiday
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
Isabella Rabinowitz, 8, has Rett Syndrome, which causes seizures and affects her motor skills and speech. Isabella's mobility had become particularly difficult for her mother, who was recovering from a double mastectomy and her father, a nurse who worked 12-hour shifts. Last year, Wish Book donors provided a lift to help ease Isabella ease into the tub at bath time. 

This holiday season, Miami Herald Charities will need your support to grant more wishes like Isabella's. Donate to Wish Book TODAY through #GiveMiamiDay, and The Miami Foundation will match a percentage of your gift. 

Link to donate: http://hrld.us/givemiamiday
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
Farm worker Lucus Atjum is a single dad raising four young children in Florida City after his wife was killed in a car accident. Last year, the family received bunk beds from an anonymous Wish Book donor, and on Christmas morning, their living room was awash in gifts. 

We have more families who need help this holiday season. And if you make a donation to the Wish Book project through #GiveMiamiDay TODAY, a percentage of your gift will be matched by The Miami Foundation. 

Link to donate: http://hrld.us/givemiamiday
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
COMPETITION UNDER WAY: Florida International University's arena was transformed Wednesday night as Miss Universe kicked off the pageant with its preliminary competition.

"I see flags from all over here," said host Roxanne Vargas.

The 88 contestants showed off their sparkling evening gowns and pink two-piece bathing suits to help the judges select the final 15. There was also a video about the women's time in Doral.

The basketball hoops were up, there were palm trees on either side of the stage and chairs were placed on the court. Hundreds filled the bleachers and floor seats cheering for their countries.

As the women were introduced, the judges and fans learned a bit about them. Some volunteered with homeless shelters. Others are studying to be lawyers and some spoke multiple languages.

At time the cheers drowned out the announcers. Fans from Colombia, Venezuela, Thailand and Mexico held flags and used noise makers.

Florida International University student Karen Rocha, 20, said she was "proud" of her school for hosting the pageant.

"This is amazing," said Rocha, who was rooting for Colombia. " This
brings worldwide attention to our school."

-- Carli Teproff
link_name: Timeline Photos

30 years ago today, NBC aired a two-hour TV movie called "Miami Vice" -- the start of a show that would change its hometown, and America's pop culture, forever. The weekly episodes began Sept. 28, 1984, and aired through May 1989. 

Check back with us this Sept. 28 as we take a look at Vice's huge impact: interviews with the stars, trivia, music, prizes, and more. (Watch full episodes at http://www.nbc.com/classic-tv/miami-vice)

status_message:

status_message:
Nou Bouke a Creole slogan that is painted on many ruinous walls throughout Port-...au-Prince, loosely translates to "We're Tired" and indeed Haitian history is tainted with daunting chapters of failed political plans and hollow promises of development. The feature-length documentary will focus on Haiti's past, present and future in light of the apocalyptic Jan. 12 earthquake that now marks a new chapter in the nation's history.

As the Caribbean nation faces perhaps its most challenging crossroads due to the immense loss of life and property resulting from the earthquake, Nou Bouke presents a comprehensive look at the Haitian polemic. It is a representative mosaic that depicts the many perspectives that surround the hopes and aspirations of the Haitian people as they move forward into a future full of uncertainty.
